Somatic SNP filtering

Ranjit Kumar


Project details: Freebayes was used to perform varint calling on tumor-matched normal samples. We have 88 vcf files, converted to tab delimted form using GATK. We added annoatations from 1000 genome, COSMIC and SNPeff. The objective is to filter germline variants from somatic ones. Ignore NF(normal frequency in further analysis).

This notebook GF1b contains exploratory analysis of the dataset with intent to dectect any outliers.

A. Load the data from previous notebook
load('all_vcf2.RData')


B1. Checking variant counts for each sample
all_vcf2 %>%
  group_by(Sample_name, Mut_type) %>%
  summarise(count=n())  %>%
  arrange(count)  %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(Sample_name, log(count)), y = log(count), fill = as.factor(Mut_type))) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge",  width = 0.8) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust=1, size=7)) +
  theme(text = element_text(size=12)) + 
  scale_fill_discrete(name = "Mutation type", labels = c("Somatic", "Germline")) +
  labs(title="Variant counts across all samples", x ="Sample_name", y = "Variant count (log)")


Note: Looks like two samples (2132_FMP000 ,C030_002870) have abnormally high somatic count indicating sample swap or contamination.


B2. Exploring TF distribution
all_vcf2 %>% 
  ggplot(aes(TF,fill = factor(Mut_type))) + 
  geom_density(alpha=0.4) +
  theme(text = element_text(size=12)) + 
  scale_fill_discrete(name = "Mutation type", labels = c("Somatic", "Germline")) +
  labs(title="Tumor frequency (TF) density plot ", x ="Tumor Frequency", y = "% variant")

Note: The TF distribution does not look natural for somatic given median at 0.5.


B3. Checking TF mean (tumor frequency mean) for each sample
  all_vcf2 %>% 
  group_by(Sample_name,Mut_type) %>% 
  summarise_at(vars(TF),list(mean=mean))  %>% 
  arrange(desc(mean))  %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(Sample_name, mean), y = mean, fill = as.factor(Mut_type) )) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge",  width = 0.8) + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust=1, size=7)) +
  theme(text = element_text(size=12)) + 
  scale_fill_discrete(name = "Mutation type", labels = c("Somatic", "Germline")) +
  labs(title="TF mean for all samples", x ="Sample name", y = "TF mean")

Note: Looks like same two samples (2132_FMP000 ,C030_002870) also have have abnormally high somatic and germline count indicating contamination and distorting TF distribution.


B4. Checking 1000 genome distribution for each sample
  all_vcf2 %>% 
  mutate(is1000g = ifelse( X1000g_AF > 0.005, 1, 0)) %>%
  group_by(Sample_name,Mut_type,is1000g) %>% 
  summarise(count=n()) %>% 
  mutate(percent = paste0(round(count/sum(count)*100,2),"%"))  %>% 
  filter(is1000g == 1) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(Sample_name, as.numeric(sub("%", "", percent))), y = as.numeric(sub("%", "", percent)), fill = as.factor(Mut_type) )) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge",  width = 0.8) + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust=1, size=7)) +
  theme(text = element_text(size=12)) +
  scale_fill_discrete(name = "Mutation type", labels = c("Somatic", "Germline")) +
  labs(title="1000 genome annotation for all samples ", x ="Sample_name", y = "% variant")

Note: The two outlier samples (2132_FMP000 ,C030_002870) has very high annotation in 1000geome annotation (for somatic variants) that means they are contaminated with normal. Overall it seems 80-90% germline variants are present in 1000 genome however only 10-20% somatic variants are present in it.


B5. So removing two outliers and saving it as all_vcf3
all_vcf3 <- 
  all_vcf2 %>% 
  filter(!(Sample_name  %in% c("2132_FMP000", "C030_002870")))

save(all_vcf3, file = "all_vcf3.RData")
